Session 2: Introduction to R.

Opening data files

There are different ways to open files. Each requires a different function. But if you install rio you may find this easier. AFTER installing that library, activate it:

library(rio)

The function you use is:

linkXL='https://github.com/UW-eScience-WinterSchool/R_Session/raw/main/demohdimil.xlsx'
dataExcel=import(linkXL)

You have the data now. You can see WHAT you have like this:

str(dataExcel)

You have the data frame you created in Python in the previous session. But you may have noticed that you have the variable Regime_type as a char, not as an ordinal. You now see you lost that in this Excel version. Let’s see the R version.

The R version does NOT use rio:

# the location
linkR='https://github.com/UW-eScience-WinterSchool/R_Session/raw/main/demohdimil.RDS'


# if location is website:
MyFile=url(linkR)

# get the data:
fromPy=readRDS(file = MyFile) # no need for a library
row.names(fromPy)=NULL   # reset indexes from Python.

Always check the data types:

Basic plotting

The most common library to prepare visuals is ggplot2. Let me show you how it works:

Let me plot HDI, a numerical variable:

library(ggplot2)
# the base has the data
base=ggplot(data=fromPy)

# then you add a particular "geom"
base + geom_histogram(aes(x=HDI))
## `stat_bin()` using `bins = 30`. Pick better value with `binwidth`.

a different geom:

base + geom_boxplot(aes(y=HDI))

Let me plot Regime type, a categorical variable:

base + geom_bar(aes(x=Regime_type))

Let me see the association between regime type and HDI:

base + geom_boxplot(aes(x=Regime_type,
                        y=HDI))

Let me see the correlation between democracy score and HDI:

base + geom_point(aes(x=DemoIndex,
                      y=HDI))

Let me see all the the correlations. For that you need the coefficients and the p_values.

library(ggcorrplot)
#all correlations:
allCorr = cor(fromPy[,c(3:7,12)])
#all p_values
allPvals=cor_pmat(fromPy[,c(3:7,12)])

This is easy using ggcorrplot:

ggcorrplot(allCorr,
           p.mat = allPvals,
           type = "lower",
           lab = TRUE,
           insig = "blank",
           tl.cex = 10)

The correlation between HDI and Military expenses, while showing Democracy Index regime type:

# save result
scat= base + geom_point(aes(HDI,
                        mil_expend,
            color=Regime_type))
# show result
scat

Let me focus on some countries:

#what countries:
some=c('Peru','United States')

# condition: if contry in some keep the name,
#            otherwise turn the name into ''.
condition=ifelse(fromPy$Country %in% some,
                 fromPy$Country,
                 '')

# on top of "scat":
scat + geom_text(x=fromPy$HDI,
                 y=fromPy$mil_expend,
                 aes(label=condition))

The geom_text requires more work, which can be eased with the help of ggrepel:

library(ggrepel)

scat + geom_text_repel(x=fromPy$HDI,
                       y=fromPy$mil_expend,
                       aes(label=condition),
                       angle=60,
                       nudge_y = 8)

Clustering via partitioning

Let’s find an alternative regime type using an advanced technique.

Part 1: Preparing data

a. Subset the data frame:

dfClus=fromPy[,c(3:7)]

b. Rename the rows:

#from
head(dfClus)
##   Electoral_process_and_pluralism Functioning_of_government
## 1                           10.00                      9.64
## 2                           10.00                      9.29
## 3                            9.58                      9.64
## 4                           10.00                      9.29
## 5                           10.00                      8.93
## 6                           10.00                      7.86
##   Political_participation Political_culture Civil_liberties
## 1                   10.00             10.00            9.71
## 2                    8.89             10.00            9.71
## 3                    8.33             10.00            9.41
## 4                    8.89              8.13           10.00
## 5                    8.89              8.75            9.71
## 6                    8.33             10.00           10.00
#to
row.names(dfClus)=fromPy$Country
head(dfClus)
##             Electoral_process_and_pluralism Functioning_of_government
## Norway                                10.00                      9.64
## Iceland                               10.00                      9.29
## Sweden                                 9.58                      9.64
## New Zealand                           10.00                      9.29
## Finland                               10.00                      8.93
## Ireland                               10.00                      7.86
##             Political_participation Political_culture Civil_liberties
## Norway                        10.00             10.00            9.71
## Iceland                        8.89             10.00            9.71
## Sweden                         8.33             10.00            9.41
## New Zealand                    8.89              8.13           10.00
## Finland                        8.89              8.75            9.71
## Ireland                        8.33             10.00           10.00

c. Keep only complete data:

dfClus=dfClus[complete.cases(dfClus),]

d. Compute distance matrix:

library(cluster)
dfClus_D=cluster::daisy(x=dfClus)

Part 2: Clustering process

1. Apply function: you need to indicate the amount of clusters required.

set.seed(123) # for replicability
numberOfClusters=4
res.pam = pam(x=dfClus_D,
              k = numberOfClusters,
              cluster.only = F)

2. Save clustering results.

fromPy$pam=res.pam$clustering

3. Verify cluster ordering.

aggregate(data=fromPy[,c(3:7,15)], .~pam,median)
##   pam Electoral_process_and_pluralism Functioning_of_government
## 1   1                            9.58                      8.39
## 2   2                            9.17                      5.71
## 3   3                            6.08                      4.64
## 4   4                            1.25                      2.50
##   Political_participation Political_culture Civil_liberties
## 1                    7.78              8.13            9.12
## 2                    6.11              5.63            7.35
## 3                    5.00              5.63            5.88
## 4                    3.33              4.38            2.94

Assign the right label:

fromPy$pam= factor(fromPy$pam,
       level=c(4,3,2,1),
       label=c(1,2,3,4),
       ordered = T)

Then,

base=ggplot(data=fromPy,
            aes(x=HDI,
                y=mil_expend,
                color=pam))
scat=base + geom_point()
scat

Part 3. Detect poor results.

The object res.pam is saving some important info. One of them is the silhouette widths. You know a case has not been well clustered if this value is negative.

# get the silhouettes widths:
eval=as.data.frame(res.pam$silinfo$widths)

# get countries poorly clustered
badPAM=eval[eval$sil_width<0,]

# result is in the row names:
badPAM=row.names(badPAM)

#these are the bad clustered countries:
badPAM
## [1] "Honduras"         "Georgia"          "Papua New Guinea" "Albania"         
## [5] "Sri Lanka"        "Thailand"

Let me show these in a scatterplot:

condition=ifelse(fromPy$Country %in% badPAM,
                 fromPy$Country,
                 '')

scat + geom_text_repel(x=fromPy$HDI,
                       y=fromPy$mil_expend,
                       label=condition,
                       angle=60,
                       nudge_y = 8)

We should see how the world looks like based on democracy clusters, follow this steps:

  1. Download the world map from here.
  2. Unzip the file you downloaded in a folder.
  3. Upload the unzipped files into MAPSHAPER. No need to uplod the text file.
  4. Transform the map into a TOPOJSON format. Save the topojson into your computer.
  5. Get a github account. Create a repository and upload the geojson file.
  6. Get the download link and use it in the next code.

Let’s add our data to the map data:

mapWorldVars=merge(mapWorld, #map first
                   fromPy, 
                   by='ISO3')

Now paint the world (get colors from here):

# what:
varToPlot=mapWorldVars$pam

#which colors:
library(RColorBrewer)
colorForScale='YlOrRd'
palette = brewer.pal(4, colorForScale)

# plotting:

## base layer - coloring missing data
plot(mapWorld,col='grey',border=0) 

## top layer
plot(mapWorldVars, col = palette[varToPlot],border=F,add=T)


legend('left', legend = c("POOR","BAD","GOOD","TOP"), 
       fill = palette,
       cex = 0.6, 
       bty = "n",
       title="Clusters")

Regression

These may be the easiest functions:

# hypothesis 1:

# The more countries expend in armed forces the better HDI 
hypo1=formula(HDI~mil_expend)
regre1=lm(hypo1,data = fromPy)

See the result:

Let’s try another hypothesis:

# hypothesis 2:

# The more countries expend in armed forces and the more democratic, the better HDI 
hypo2=formula(HDI~mil_expend  + DemoIndex)
regre2=lm(hypo2,data = fromPy)
